cs.LO, cs.GT, cs.AI, cs.DS, cs.CC

The paper discusses the connection between games and computation, which suggests that it could belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. The paper also introduces and investigates a range of general notions of a game, which could place it in the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses modeling partial and erroneous information, which could suggest it belongs to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the connection to logic and computation formalisms, which could place it in the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the recently introduced Turing-complete logic based on game-theoretic semantics, which could suggest it belongs to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category.
